    Q. 7

    Which of the following claims correct about strict 2PL?
    I. Guaranteed conflict serializability
    II. Guaranteed strict recoverable
    III. Guaranteed deadlock avoidance

    Have any Doubt ? Solution Video
    A I, II only Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (a)
    Every 2PL is conflict serializable, and every strict 2PL is always guaranteed to be strict recoverable but not deadlock free.

    B I only Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (a)
    Every 2PL is conflict serializable, and every strict 2PL is always guaranteed to be strict recoverable but not deadlock free.

    C I, II, III Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (a)
    Every 2PL is conflict serializable, and every strict 2PL is always guaranteed to be strict recoverable but not deadlock free.

    D II, III only Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (a)
    Every 2PL is conflict serializable, and every strict 2PL is always guaranteed to be strict recoverable but not deadlock free.

    Q. 8

    Consider the following locking protocol:
    I. Transaction must lock all data items before begins any read or write operation.
    II. Transaction executes all read and write operations alongwith transaction commit.
    III. Transaction unlocks all data items.
    Which of the following is true about given protocol?

    Have any Doubt ? Solution Video
    A Guaranteed no deadlock and guaranteed strict recoverability but may not serializable. Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (c)
    Since transaction lock all data items before any operation, so no deadlock. According to II and III claims transaction works like strict 2PL which ensure serializable and strict recoverability.

    B Guaranteed no deadlock and guaranteed no starvation. Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (c)
    Since transaction lock all data items before any operation, so no deadlock. According to II and III claims transaction works like strict 2PL which ensure serializable and strict recoverability.

    C Guaranteed no deadlock, guaranteed serializability and strict recoverability. Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (c)
    Since transaction lock all data items before any operation, so no deadlock. According to II and III claims transaction works like strict 2PL which ensure serializable and strict recoverability.

    D Guaranteed serializable and no deadlocks and may not strict recoverable. Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (c)
    Since transaction lock all data items before any operation, so no deadlock. According to II and III claims transaction works like strict 2PL which ensure serializable and strict recoverability.

    Q. 10

    Which of the following statement is/are true?

    Have any Doubt ?
    A For any data file it is possible to construct two separate sparse first level indexes on different keys. Your answer is Wrong Correct Option
    Solution :

    (b)
    For any data file, it is possible to construct two separate dense first level indexes on different keys i.e., a file is stored based on one key (i.e., sorted order). So, two or more first level dense index are possible on different keys.

    B For any data file, it is possible to construct two separate dense first level indexes on different keys. Your answer is Wrong Correct Option
    Solution :

    (b)
    For any data file, it is possible to construct two separate dense first level indexes on different keys i.e., a file is stored based on one key (i.e., sorted order). So, two or more first level dense index are possible on different keys.

    C For any data file, it is possible to construct a sparse first level index and a dense second level index,both should be useful. Your answer is Wrong Correct Option
    Solution :

    (b)
    For any data file, it is possible to construct two separate dense first level indexes on different keys i.e., a file is stored based on one key (i.e., sorted order). So, two or more first level dense index are possible on different keys.

    D All the above Your answer is Wrong Correct Option
    Solution :

    (b)
    For any data file, it is possible to construct two separate dense first level indexes on different keys i.e., a file is stored based on one key (i.e., sorted order). So, two or more first level dense index are possible on different keys.

    Q. 17

    Consider the following Relational Schema R(ABCDEF ) and functional dependency set:
    {AB → C, C → A, BC → D, ACD → B, BE → C, EC → AF, CF → BD, D → E}
    What is highest normal form satisfied by relation R?

    Have any Doubt ? Solution Video
    A 1NF Your answer is Correct
    Solution :

    (c)
    The given relation with functional dependencies is in 3NF i.e., no transitive and partial function dependency exist but C → A, violets BCNF i.e., super key → any attributes. So, relation R in 3NF but not BCNF.

    Solution :

    2

    • Only serial schedules T1 → T2, T2 → T1 are conflict serializable.
    • None of non serial schedules are conflict serializable.
